headline: [TIR] Handle subroutine calls in MakeUnpackedAPI
body:
Prior to this commit, MakeUnpackedAPI required all functions to be
annotated with `kGlobalSymbol` (`"global_symbol"`).  This commit
updates the transformation to apply only to functions that have the
`kGlobalSymbol` attribute, and to update any internal callsites of the
modified functions.

This is analogous to the changes made in
https://github.com/apache/tvm/pull/14913, which updates
`MakePackedAPI`.
author: Lunderberg

headline: [Unity]Support causal mask for `R.nn.attention`
body:
This PR introduces the causal mask for `R.nn.attention` and its cutlass dispatch and legalization. The `causal_mask` argument accepts 2 types of causal masks - "TopLeft" and "BottomRight".
For example, with `seq_len = 4`, `seq_len_kv = 2`,
mask for "TopLeft":
[[1, 0],
 [1, 1],
 [1, 1],
 [1, 1]]
mask for "BottomRight":
[[1, 1],
 [1, 1],
 [1, 1],
 [1, 1]]
with `seq_len = 2`, `seq_len_kv = 4`,
mask for "TopLeft":
[[1, 0, 0, 0],
 [1, 1, 0, 0]]
mask for "BottomRight":
[[1, 1, 1, 0],
 [1, 1, 1, 1]]
author: cyx-6

The "before" cases must have SSA violations, which is not valid in

introduce SSA violations through the Python API, to avoid this

author: Lunderberg

headline: [TVMScript] Round-trip DeclBuffer with undefined data pointer
body:
Previously, a `DeclBuffer` object in which `decl_buffer->buffer->data`
had not been defined would be printed without the `data` argument.
This was the same representation as the `Allocate`/`DeclBuffer`
pattern (e.g. `buf = T.decl_buffer(shape,dtype)`), and so the
`Allocate` node would be inserted when parsing.

This commit updates the printing of buffers to be aware of which
variables are implicitly declared in the process of declaring a
buffer.  (e.g. A buffer that occurs in `BlockNode::alloc_buffers`
defines both the buffer and the data pointer, while a `DeclBuffer`
only defines the buffer.)  This is used to produce a different
representation for the undefined data pointer, removing the ambiguity
with the `Allocate`/`DeclBuffer` sugar.

Because this change only affects malformed TIR in which a `DeclBuffer`
node references an undefined data pointer, it is intended primarily
for debugging purposes.
author: Lunderberg
pr_title: [TVMScript] Round-trip DeclBuffer with undefined data pointer

headline: [TIR] Refactor SplitHostDevice into three separate passes
body:
First pass, `AnnotateDeviceRegions`.  This pass decides which portions
of a PrimFunc should be run on the device, and annotates them with
`kTarget` attribute, indicating which target should be used for later
lowering steps.

Second pass, `SplitHostDevice`.  This pass extracts the annotated
region into an independent PrimFunc.  The `kTarget` attribute of the
extracted kernel is defined by the `kTarget` annotation inserted by
`AnnotateDeviceRegions`.  This occurs prior to `MakePackedAPI`.

Third pass, `LowerDeviceKernelLaunch`.  This pass identifies
subroutine calls that call into device kernels, and rewrites them into
`T.tvm_call_packed`.  This occurs after `MakePackedAPI`.
author: Lunderberg
pr_title: [TIR] Support PrimFunc-to-PrimFunc calls with primitive arguments

headline: [Driver] Single-module lowering flow in driver_api.cc
body:
Prior to this commit, a build that used multiple targets needed to
provide `tvm::build` with a `Map<Target, IRModule>` specifying which
target should be used to compile each `IRModule`.  As a result,
lowering passes could not introduce new targets based on a PrimFunc's
content (e.g. a `with T.target()` frame to delegate out to another
device), nor simplify based on cross-device subroutines (e.g. simplify
a host-side conditional based on the known output of a device-side
internal subroutine).

This commit makes the `tvm::attr::kTarget` attribute (`"target"`) be
the single source of truth for where a `PrimFunc` will be executed.
Other existing methods for specifying the target (the `target`
parameter for `tvm.build`, the keys in a `Map<Target,IRModule>`, the
parameter to the pass `tir::transform::BindTarget`) are still accepted
as inputs, and may provide a default value for `tvm::attr::kTarget` if
the attribute is missing, but may not overwrite the target attribute.

This is part of a series of commits to simplify the handling of
multi-target builds.
author: Lunderberg
pr_title: [TIR] Support PrimFunc-to-PrimFunc calls with primitive arguments

headline: [TIR] Check kIsHostFunc in CombineContextCall and BuiltinLower
body:
These lowering passes should only alter functions that occur on the
host side after `tir.SplitHostDevice`.

This is part of a series of commits to simplify the handling of
multi-target builds.  By ignoring device-side functions, these passes
can be applied to a mixed `IRModule` containing both host- and
device-side functions.
author: Lunderberg
pr_title: [TIR] Support PrimFunc-to-PrimFunc calls with primitive arguments

headline: [TIR] Refactor SplitHostDevice into three separate passes
body:
First pass, `AnnotateDeviceRegions`.  This pass decides which portions
of a PrimFunc should be run on the device, and annotates them with
`kTarget` attribute, indicating which target should be used for later
lowering steps.

Second pass, `SplitHostDevice`.  This pass extracts the annotated
region into an independent PrimFunc.  The `kTarget` attribute of the
extracted kernel is defined by the `kTarget` annotation inserted by
`AnnotateDeviceRegions`.  The host function is marked by the
`tvm::tir::attr::kIsHostFunc` attribute, allowing it to be recognized
by later host-only lowering passes.

Third pass, `LowerDeviceKernelLaunch`.  This pass identifies
subroutine calls that call into device kernels, and rewrites them into
`T.tvm_call_packed`.
author: Lunderberg

headline: [TIR] Apply the kIsHostFunc attribute to SplitHostDevice output
body:
Previously, the host function generated by `tir.SplitHostDevice` was
stripped of any `tvm::attr::kTarget` annotation.  This commit updates
the `tir.SplitHostDevice` pass so that it replaces the
`tvm::attr::kTarget` annotation with the host, and also inserts a
`tvm::tir::attr::kIsHostFunc` attribute.

This is part of a series of commits to simplify the handling of
multi-target builds.  By tracking the host functions separately,
passes that previously applied to just the host `IRModule` can be
applied to the merged host/device `IRModule`, while only altering the
host functions.
author: Lunderberg
pr_title: [TIR] Support PrimFunc-to-PrimFunc calls with primitive arguments

headline: [TIR] Retain kIsHostFunc, previous kTarget, in BindTarget
body:
Prior to this commit, the `tir.BindTarget` pass would strip out any
`tvm::tir::attr::kIsHostFunc` attributes (`"tir.is_host_func"`), and
would replace any prior `tvm::attr::kTarget` attributes (`"target"`).
This commit updates the behavior so that any previously defined
attributes for `tvm::attr::kTarget` are kept unmodified, and the
`tvm::tir::attr::kIsHostFunc` attribute is retained in the output.

This is part of a series of commits to simplify the handling of
multi-target builds.
author: Lunderberg
pr_title: [TIR] Support PrimFunc-to-PrimFunc calls with primitive arguments

contain only a single PrimFunc.  This commit relaxes the requirement,
to require a single host-side PrimFunc, and to ignore any other

headline: [CodeGen][LLVM] Codegen to generate internal functions
body:
Previously, `CodeGenLLVM` required all TIR PrimFuncs to have the
`kGlobalSymbol` attribute, using its value as the externally-visible
symbol in the generated library.  This commit relaxes that
requirement, using the presence of `kGlobalSymbol` to indicate whether
a function should be exposed externally.  If `kGlobalSymbol` is not
defined, then the symbol name is generated from the name of the
`tvm::GlobalVar` with the prefix `"_internal_"`, and the symbol is not
exposed externally.

Since this does not change the codegen behavior for any function that
was previously supported, this is not a breaking change.
author: Lunderberg
pr_title: [LLVM] Codegen subroutine call when CallNode::op is GlobalVar
